Computer Networks – BSc CSIT 4th Semester – Simplified Unit-wise Syllabus
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Unit I: Introduction to Computer Network (6 Hours)

Fundamentals: definitions, advantages, use cases

Network topologies (Star, Tree, Bus, Mesh, etc.)

Network types: PAN, LAN, CAN, MAN, WAN

Communication models: Client–Server, Peer-to-Peer (P2P)

Protocols vs Standards (syntax, semantics, timing; de jure vs de facto; standards bodies)

OSI Model overview vs TCP/IP Model, plus their comparison

Connection‑oriented vs connectionless services

Overview: Internet structure, ISPs, backbone networks

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Unit II: Physical Layer & Network Media (4 Hours)

Network devices: repeater, hub, switch, bridge, router

Transmission media:

Wired: twisted pair, coaxial, fiber optic

Wireless: radio waves, microwaves, infrared

Ethernet cabling standards (UTP, fiber optics)

Switching methods: circuit switching, message switching, packet switching

ISDN overview: interfaces and standards

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Unit III: Data Link Layer (8 Hours)

Functions of the Data Link Layer (DLL)

Logical Link Control (LLC) vs Media Access Control (MAC)

Framing and flow control mechanisms

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Unit IV: Network Layer (10 Hours)

(Although not detailed in earlier search, standard content implies focus on IP addressing, routing,
  and related protocols—based on course objectives)

IPv4 and IPv6 addressing and subnetting

Routing fundamentals: static vs dynamic, interior/exterior routing (e.g., RIP, OSPF, BGP)

Core functions of routers and network layer protocols

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Unit V: Transport Layer (6 Hours)

Basic transport layer concepts: functions, protocols, reliability, flow control, error control

Common protocols like TCP vs UDP (implied by standard structure)

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Unit VI: Application Layer (7 Hours)

High-level protocols and services: HTTP, FTP, SMTP, DNS, etc.

Basics of multimedia networking and streaming protocols

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Unit VII: Multimedia & Future Networking (4 Hours)

Multimedia networking concepts

Emerging and future networking technologies (e.g., IoT, 5G, SDN, etc.)

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

At‑a‑Glance Overview
Unit	Topics Covered
I	Intro to networks, topologies, OSI/TCP models
II	Physical layer: devices & media types
III	Data Link Layer: framing, MAC, LLC
IV	Network Layer: routing & addressing
V	Transport Layer: protocols like TCP/UDP
VI	Application Layer: key services & protocols
VII	Multimedia & upcoming networking trends
Tips to Nail the Board Exam (As a Pro)

Draw visuals: OSI/TCP models, frame formats, and media types.

Memorize fundamentals: Topology names, protocol layers, device functions.

Apply examples: IPv4 vs IPv6, sample subnetting, typical use cases.

Stay current: Know at least one emerging tech (e.g., SDN, IoT) for extra edge.
